    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {d^{2}x^{\lambda } \over dT^{2}}=-\Gamma _{\nu \alpha }^{\lambda }{dx^{\nu } \over dT}{dx^{\alpha } \over dT}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="../I/b0523bac4f924baecb32c330219a0a289d3cd2b9.svg" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.171ex; width:23.941ex; height:6.009ex;" alt="{\displaystyle {d^{2}x^{\lambda } \over dT^{2}}=-\Gamma _{\nu \alpha }^{\lambda }{dx^{\nu } \over dT}{dx^{\alpha } \over dT}.}" loading="lazy"></span></dd></dl>

<p id="mwYA">Notice that, if we had used the proper time “s” as the parameter of motion, instead of using the locally inertial time coordinate “T”, then our derivation of the geodesic equation of motion would be complete.  In any event, let us continue by applying the one-dimensional <a href="Chain_rule" title="Chain rule" id="mwYQ">chain rule</a>:</p>
